If any of these numbers is divisible by $n$, then the statement of the problem is true. Otherwise, when divided by $n$, these numbers give remainders, among which there will be no more than $n-1$ different ones. Since there are $n$ numbers, at least two remainders will coincide. Then the difference of the numbers with coinciding remainders is divisible by $n$. But this difference is in any case either one of the given numbers or the sum of several consecutive numbers.

